hook.real_world_problem:
Get the names of all in-stock Electronics products with price under ₹2000, sorted by rating descending, as a comma-separated string.

**Before streams (Module 6 style — 15 lines):**
```java
List<String> result = new ArrayList<>();
for (Product p : catalog) {
    if (p.isInStock() &&
        p.getCategory().equals("Electronics") &&
        p.getPrice() < 2000) {
        result.add(p.getName());
    }
}
result.sort((a, b) -> {
    double ra = findByName(a).getRating();
    double rb = findByName(b).getRating();
    return Double.compare(rb, ra);
});
String joined = String.join(", ", result);
```

**After streams (1 line + continuation):**
```java
String joined = catalog.stream()
    .filter(p -> p.isInStock() && p.getCategory().equals("Electronics") && p.getPrice() < 2000)
    .sorted((a, b) -> Double.compare(b.getRating(), a.getRating()))
    .map(Product::getName)
    .collect(Collectors.joining(", "));
```

Same result. Clearer intent. Fewer moving parts. No temporary list. This is the Stream API — a declarative, composable way to process sequences of data.

You already know all the functional interfaces it uses (Predicate, Function, Consumer, Supplier). Today you learn the API that puts them to work at scale.

concept_explanation.stream_creation:
**Creating Streams:**

```java
import java.util.stream.*;

// From collection
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Aisha", "Raj");
Stream<String> s1 = names.stream();

// From array
String[] arr = {"A", "B", "C"};
Stream<String> s2 = Arrays.stream(arr);

// From values directly
Stream<Integer> s3 = Stream.of(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);

// Empty stream
Stream<String> empty = Stream.empty();

// Infinite streams (with limit)
Stream<Integer> natural = Stream.iterate(1, n -> n + 1);  // 1, 2, 3, ...
Stream<Double> randoms  = Stream.generate(Math::random);   // endless randoms
// Always limit infinite streams!
natural.limit(10).forEach(System.out::println); // prints 1-10

// Primitive streams (more efficient for numbers)
IntStream nums    = IntStream.range(1, 6);    // 1,2,3,4,5
IntStream range   = IntStream.rangeClosed(1, 5); // 1,2,3,4,5 inclusive
DoubleStream dbl  = DoubleStream.of(1.1, 2.2, 3.3);
```

concept_explanation.sorted_distinct_limit_skip:
**Sorting and slicing:**

```java
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(5, 3, 8, 1, 3, 9, 2);

// sorted() — natural order
nums.stream().sorted().forEach(System.out::print);  // 1 2 3 3 5 8 9

// sorted(Comparator) — custom order
catalog.stream()
    .sorted((a, b) -> Double.compare(b.getPrice(), a.getPrice()))  // desc price
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

// distinct() — remove duplicates (uses equals)
nums.stream().distinct().forEach(System.out::print);  // 5 3 8 1 9 2

// limit(n) — take first n elements
nums.stream().sorted().limit(3).forEach(System.out::print);  // 1 2 3

// skip(n) — skip first n, take the rest
nums.stream().sorted().skip(3).forEach(System.out::print);   // 3 5 8 9

// Combined — pagination:
List<Product> page2 = catalog.stream()
    .sorted(Comparator.comparing(Product::getName))
    .skip(10)   // skip page 1 (10 items)
    .limit(10)  // take page 2 (10 items)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
```

concept_explanation.terminal_collect:
**`collect(Collectors.toList())`** — the most common terminal operation:

```java
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

// Collect to List
List<String> filtered = names.stream()
    .filter(s -> s.length() > 3)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

// Collect to Set (deduplicates)
Set<String> unique = names.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.toSet());

// Join strings
String joined = names.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.joining(", "));  // 'Aisha, Raj, Priya'

String formatted = names.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.joining(", ", "[", "]"));  // '[Aisha, Raj, Priya]'

// Count with filter
long count = names.stream()
    .filter(s -> s.length() > 3)
    .count();
```

concept_explanation.terminal_find_match:
**Finding and matching — short-circuit terminal operations:**

```java
// count — total elements after pipeline
long n = names.stream().filter(s -> s.startsWith("A")).count();  // 1

// findFirst — first element (or empty Optional)
Optional<String> first = names.stream()
    .filter(s -> s.length() > 4)
    .findFirst();  // Optional[Aisha]
first.ifPresent(System.out::println);  // prints Aisha
String orDefault = first.orElse("none");

// anyMatch — does ANY element satisfy condition?
boolean hasLong = names.stream().anyMatch(s -> s.length() > 5);  // false

// allMatch — do ALL elements satisfy condition?
boolean allNonEmpty = names.stream().allMatch(s -> !s.isEmpty());  // true

// noneMatch — do NO elements satisfy condition?
boolean noneShort = names.stream().noneMatch(s -> s.length() < 3);  // true

// min / max
Optional<Integer> max = nums.stream().max(Integer::compare);  // Optional[9]
Optional<String> shortest = names.stream().min(Comparator.comparingInt(String::length));
```

`Optional<T>` is returned for operations that might not find anything. Always handle with `orElse()`, `ifPresent()`, or `isPresent()` — never call `get()` without checking!

concept_explanation.reduce:
**`reduce`** — combine all elements into one value:

```java
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);

// Sum with reduce
Optional<Integer> sum = nums.stream()
    .reduce((a, b) -> a + b);   // Optional[15]

// Sum with identity (starting value)
int sum2 = nums.stream()
    .reduce(0, (a, b) -> a + b); // 15 — not Optional (has default)

// Product
int product = nums.stream()
    .reduce(1, (a, b) -> a * b); // 120

// For numbers — prefer sum()/average() via mapToInt:
int total = nums.stream().mapToInt(Integer::intValue).sum();
```

**Note**: for simple aggregations (sum, count, average, min, max) on primitive streams, prefer `IntStream.sum()`, `IntStream.average()` etc. — more readable and slightly more efficient.

concept_explanation.lazy_evaluation:
**Lazy evaluation** — intermediate operations only run when terminal operation is called:

```java
// Nothing executes until the terminal operation (forEach)
Stream<String> pipeline = names.stream()
    .filter(s -> {
        System.out.println("filtering: " + s);  // won't print yet
        return s.length() > 3;
    })
    .map(s -> {
        System.out.println("mapping: " + s);    // won't print yet
        return s.toUpperCase();
    });

// NOW it executes (terminal operation triggers the pipeline):
pipeline.forEach(System.out::println);
```

**Why lazy is good**: filter reduces the set BEFORE map runs. If filter leaves 3 elements from 1000, map only runs 3 times. Efficient.

**Short-circuit optimization**: `findFirst()` stops the pipeline as soon as the first matching element is found — doesn't process remaining elements.

**One-time use**: once a stream's terminal operation runs, the stream is closed. Calling another terminal operation throws `IllegalStateException: stream has already been operated upon or closed`.

